  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Before going off to sleep patients are given oxygen to saturate blood with oxygen to extend
      time before a decrease in the level of oxygen in the blood occurs. During this period, obese
      patients have a faster decrease in the level of oxygen in their blood. This study uses a
      device called &quot;high-flow nasal cannula&quot; (HFNC), which delivers humidified high-flow oxygen
      through 2 small plastic tubes placed just inside nostrils. In the intensive care unit
      settings this device has been used extensively and has become a standard practice. Purpose of
      this study is to determine whether these high-flow nasal cannula increase the time safely
      when going to sleep during elective surgery.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
